<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-656-803  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 656 803.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Nov 26 1990 n328 p34(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FCC's role in int'l rates: Who should regulate? (includes arelated article on who pays what on overseas calls)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rocks, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) is planning to attackunfairly high international telephone tariffs, but US carriersprefer to negotiate international rates themselves.andP;  Smallercompanies are asking the FCC to ensure that they will beguaranteed any reductions in rates negotiated by ATandamp;T, thedominant US carrier.andP;  The current system of accounting rates meansUS customers subsidize foreign carriers that charge more for theirservices than US carriers.andP;  There are normally twice the number ofoutbound calls from the US than there are US-bound calls fromother countries, due to the lower rates in the US.andP;  This imbalanceresults in US companies sending millions of dollars overseas everymonth.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     International CommunicationsTelecommunications ServicesCost of CommunicationsCost ReductionUnited States. Federal Communications CommissionGovernment RegulationTariff.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>